At some past Casualty Actuarial Society meetings and seminars I have
handed out scripts of R code that facilitate the exchange of data
between R and Excel. The scripts perform Input/Output via the
clipboard, via csv files, and directly -- a total of six functions.

Surprisingly, the clipboard is a useful medium for exchanging small
amounts of data with Excel. For large amounts of data, as others have
noted, databases and csv files are usually more appropriate. The
disadvantage of importing data to R using my character-based methods
include

1. a potential lack of floating point precision,
2. translating amounts from currency etc. to R numerics,
3. translating dates to R time-oriented objects (Date, POSIXt, etc.),
4. interpreting NA's on input and output.

My scripts ignore the first issue but attempt to deal with the others
in (hopefully) "intuitive" ways that make sense in situations
actuaries tend to face.

I used your post, Edward, as an opportunity to share those scripts
with a broader audience. See the open-source 'excelRio' package on
github at https://github.com/trinostics/excelRio, including
instructions, copied from Markus' ChainLadder repository, on how to
download and install (thank you, Markus!).

Note that to exchange data directly requires other R packages (e.g.,
XLConnect, as with Brian's MRMR package). Those other packages, in
turn, rely on other software -- e.g., java or perl -- that can be
troublesome to administer on some systems.

As a result, I encourage R newcomers to use the clipboard as much as
possible. The clipboard functions are pasteFromExcel and copyToExcel
preceded/followed by, respectively, Ctrl-C/Ctrl-V in Excel. (On a mac
use the apple key r.t. ctrl.)

Let me know if you have any questions, or if any behavior does not
meet your intuition.

Thanks,
Dan

